            <section class="mt-8 prose">
              <h2>How this travel budget calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed to be more flexible than a simple “daily
                budget” app. It separates
                <strong>one-time trip costs</strong> (like flights and
                insurance) from <strong>daily living costs</strong> (like food
                and accommodation), supports
                <strong>multiple travelers</strong>, and builds a
                <strong>savings plan</strong> for you.
              </p>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. One-time costs (all travelers)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( C_{\text{one-time}} = C_{\text{flights}} +
                  C_{\text{accommodation, prepaid}} + C_{\text{transport,
                  fixed}} + C_{\text{visa}} + C_{\text{insurance}} +
                  C_{\text{gear}} + C_{\text{activities, fixed}} +
                  C_{\text{other}} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>2. Daily costs (all travelers)</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  First compute per-person daily total: \( C_{\text{daily, per
                  person}} = C_{\text{accommodation}} + C_{\text{food}} +
                  C_{\text{transport}} + C_{\text{activities}} + C_{\text{misc}}
                  + C_{\text{workspace}} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Then scale by days and travelers: \( C_{\text{daily, total}} =
                  C_{\text{daily, per person}} \times \text{days} \times
                  \text{travelers} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>3. Subtotal and buffer</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( C_{\text{subtotal}} = C_{\text{one-time}} + C_{\text{daily,
                  total}} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( C_{\text{buffer}} = C_{\text{subtotal}} \times
                  \frac{\text{buffer\%}}{100} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( C_{\text{total}} = C_{\text{subtotal}} + C_{\text{buffer}}
                  \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>4. Per person and per day</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( C_{\text{per person}} =
                  \dfrac{C_{\text{total}}}{\text{travelers}} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( C_{\text{per day (trip)}} =
                  \dfrac{C_{\text{total}}}{\text{days}} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( C_{\text{per day per person}} =
                  \dfrac{C_{\text{total}}}{\text{days} \times \text{travelers}}
                  \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>5. Savings plan</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Remaining to save: \( C_{\text{remaining}} = \max\left(0,\;
                  C_{\text{total}} - C_{\text{already saved}}\right) \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Monthly savings: \( S_{\text{month}} =
                  \dfrac{C_{\text{remaining}}}{\text{months until trip}} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Weekly savings (approx.): \( S_{\text{week}} =
                  \dfrac{S_{\text{month}} \times 12}{52} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to build a realistic travel budget</h2>
              <p>
                A good travel budget is detailed enough to avoid surprises, but
                simple enough that you’ll actually use it. Here’s how to
                approach each section of the calculator.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Estimate one-time trip costs</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Flights:</strong> include checked baggage, seat
                  selection, and airport transfers if they’re fixed.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Visas & entry fees:</strong> check official government
                  sites for up-to-date prices.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Insurance:</strong> travel medical + trip cancellation
                  if needed.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Gear & luggage:</strong> backpacks, adapters,
                  clothing, etc. that you’re buying specifically for this trip.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pre-booked tours:</strong> multi-day tours, attraction
                  passes, or activities you pay for in advance.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Estimate daily costs by travel style</h3>
              <p>
                Daily costs depend heavily on destination and comfort level. As
                a rough starting point:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Budget:</strong> hostels, street food, public
                  transport, free activities.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Mid-range:</strong> guesthouses/hotels, restaurant
                  meals, some paid activities.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Comfort:</strong> hotels/apartments, taxis, tours,
                  higher-end dining.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use guidebooks, blogs, or country-level budget sites to get
                typical prices, then plug them into the daily section of the
                calculator.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Add a realistic buffer</h3>
              <p>
                Prices change, plans change, and unexpected costs always appear.
                Many experienced travelers add a
                <strong>10–20% buffer</strong> on top of their estimated costs.
                In this tool you can set any buffer percentage and immediately
                see the impact.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Turn your budget into a savings plan</h3>
              <p>
                Once you know your total trip cost, the key question is:
                <em>Can I afford it by my departure date?</em>
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Enter how much you’ve already saved for travel.</li>
                <li>Enter how many months you have until you leave.</li>
                <li>
                  Compare the required monthly savings with what you can
                  realistically set aside.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                If the monthly savings target is too high, consider shortening
                the trip, choosing a cheaper destination, traveling in shoulder
                season, or pushing the departure date.
              </p>

              <h2>Example: 10-day city break for two</h2>
              <p>Suppose you’re planning a 10-day trip for two people:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Flights: 900</li>
                <li>Insurance: 80</li>
                <li>Pre-booked tours: 200</li>
                <li>
                  Daily per person: 50 (accommodation) + 30 (food) + 10
                  (transport) + 20 (activities) + 10 (misc) = 120
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>With 10 days and 2 travelers:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Daily costs total: 120 × 10 × 2 = 2,400</li>
                <li>One-time costs total: 900 + 80 + 200 = 1,180</li>
                <li>Subtotal: 3,580</li>
                <li>Buffer 15%: 537</li>
                <li><strong>Total trip cost ≈ 4,117</strong></li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you’ve already saved 1,000 and you leave in 8 months, you
                need to save about 389 per month. The calculator does all of
                this math for you instantly.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What should I include in a travel budget?</h3>
              <p>
                Include every cost you’re likely to pay because of the trip:
                transport, accommodation, food, activities, insurance, visas,
                gear, and a buffer for surprises. It’s better to slightly
                overestimate than to run out of money on the road.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I budget for variable exchange rates?</h3>
              <p>
                Choose a single “home” currency (like USD or EUR) and convert
                all estimates into that currency using today’s rate. Add a
                slightly higher buffer (e.g., 20%) to protect against currency
                swings and inflation.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should I update my travel budget?</h3>
              <p>
                Update it whenever a major cost changes: you find cheaper
                flights, add a new tour, or change your travel dates. Many
                travelers review their budget monthly while saving, and daily or
                weekly while on the trip.
              </p>
